The paper discusses the use of the plasmodium of Physarum polycephalum as a substrate for non-classical, nature-inspired computing devices, which suggests a focus on robotics and artificial intelligence (cs.RO and cs.AI). The plasmodium's unique properties also make it an ideal candidate for distributed inputs and outputs, which could fall under the category of systems and control (cs.SY). The paper also mentions the plasmodium's primitive memory and decision making, which could involve neural networks and machine learning (cs.NE). Finally, the paper discusses the plasmodium's potential as an amorphous biological robot, which falls under the category of bio-inspired computing (cs.BIO).
